body:
I'm using iverilog 10.1 on x64 win7 system with "iverlog -v" outputs:

$ iverilog -v
Icarus Verilog version 10.1 (stable) (v10_1_1)

Copyright 1998-2015 Stephen Williams

When I simulating my serial divider, I found that divide overflow of 32-bit integers:
$signed(32'h8000_0000) / $signed(32'hFFFF_FFFF) 
is not detected by vvp and will stall the program when evaluating the expression.

My test program is:

module divov1;
  reg [31:0] q1;
  reg [31:0] q2;
  reg [31:0] quotient;
  initial begin
    q1 = 32'h8000_0000;
    q2 = 32'hFFFF_FFFF;
    quotient = $signed(q1) / $signed(q2);
    $display("quotient = 0x%08h;", quotient);
    $finish;
  end
endmodule // divov1

Executing the test program never returns to the shell (cygwin) or cmd.exe.

$vvp divov.vvp


I also tested wider (64-bit) and narrower (16-bit) integers. Both of them didn't stall the program.

The 64-bit test program is:

module divov2;
  reg [63:0] q1;
  reg [63:0] q2;
  reg [63:0] quotient;
  initial begin
    q1 = 64'h8000_0000_0000_0000;
    q2 = 64'hFFFF_FFFF_FFFF_FFFF;
    quotient = $signed(q1) / $signed(q2);
    $display("quotient = 0x%016h;", quotient);
    $finish;
  end
endmodule // divov2

The output of 64-bit test program is:

$ vvp divov2.vvp
quotient = 0x8000000000000000;

The 16-bit test program is

module divov3;
  reg [15:0] q1;
  reg [15:0] q2;
  reg [15:0] quotient;
  initial begin
    q1 = 16'h8000;
    q2 = 16'hFFFF;
    quotient = $signed(q1) / $signed(q2);
    $display("quotient = 0x%04h;", quotient);
    $finish;
  end
endmodule // divov3

The output of 16-bit test program is:

$ vvp divov3.vvp
quotient = 0x8000;
